"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Sitch et al. 2008)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Sitch et al. 2008)", "formattedCitation": "(}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_10}\proptype30{\staticval bal carbon cycle. The DGVMs are also coupled to a fast 'climate analogue model', based on the Hadley Centre General Circulation Model (GCM), and run into the future for four Special Report Emission Scenarios (SRES): A1FI, A2, B1, B2. Results show that all}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_11}\proptype30{\staticval  DGVMs are consistent with the contemporary global land carbon budget. Under the more extreme projections of future environmental change, the responses of the DGVMs diverge markedly. In particular, large uncertainties are associated with the response of t}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_12}\proptype30{\staticval ropical vegetation to drought and boreal ecosystems to elevated temperatures and changing soil moisture status. The DGVMs show more divergence in their response to regional changes in climate than to increases in atmospheric CO2 content. All models simula}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_13}\proptype30{\staticval te a release of land carbon in response to climate, when physiological effects of elevated atmospheric CO2 on plant production are not considered, implying a positive terrestrial climate-carbon cycle feedback. All DGVMs simulate a reduction in global net }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_14}\proptype30{\staticval primary production (NPP) and a decrease in soil residence time in the tropics and extra-tropics in response to future climate. When both counteracting effects of climate and atmospheric CO2 on ecosystem function are considered, all the DGVMs simulate cumu}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_15}\proptype30{\staticval lative net land carbon uptake over the 21st century for the four SRES emission scenarios. However, for the most extreme A1FI emissions scenario, three out of five DGVMs simulate an annual net source of CO2 from the land to the atmosphere in the final deca}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_16}\proptype30{\staticval des of the 21st century. For this scenario, cumulative land uptake differs by 494\\u00a0Pg\\u00a0C among DGVMs over the 21st century. This uncertainty is equivalent to over 50 years of anthropogenic emissions at current levels.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [[}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_17}\proptype30{\staticval "2008"]]\}, "title": "Evaluation of the terrestrial carbon cycle, future plant geography and climate-carbon cycle feedbacks using five Dynamic Global Vegetation Models (DGVMs)", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_18}\proptype30{\staticval d098621a-b04a-4389-8032-5975c4ab6f16"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_2}\proptype30{\staticval Sitch et al. 2008)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Global Change Biology", "ISSN": "13541013", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Sitch", "parse-names": false, "given": "Stepha}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_3}\proptype30{\staticval n"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Huntingford", "parse-names": false, "given": "C."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Gedney", "parse-names": false, "given"}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_4}\proptype30{\staticval : "N."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Levy", "parse-names": false, "given": "P. E."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Lomas", "parse-names": false, "given":}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_5}\proptype30{\staticval  "M."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Piao", "parse-names": false, "given": "S. L."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Betts", "parse-names": false, "given": }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_6}\proptype30{\staticval "R."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Ciais", "parse-names": false, "given": "P."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Cox", "parse-names": false, "given": "P."\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_7}\proptype30{\staticval , \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Friedlingstein", "parse-names": false, "given": "P."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Jones", "parse-names": false, "given":}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_8}\proptype30{\staticval  "C. D."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Prentice", "parse-names": false, "given": "I. C."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Woodward", "parse-names": false,}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8JfNlpI0I5_9}\proptype30{\staticval  "given": "F. I."\}], "id": "ITEM-1", "DOI": "10.1111/j.1365-2486.2008.01626.x", "abstract": "This study tests the ability of five Dynamic Global Vegetation Models (DGVMs), forced with observed climatology and atmospheric CO2, to model the contemporary glo}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Purvis et al. 2000; Davies and Buckley 2011)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Purvis et al. 2000}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_10}\proptype30{\staticval ames": false, "given": "Lauren B."\}], "id": "ITEM-2", "DOI": "10.1098/rstb.2011.0058", "abstract": "Phylogenetic diversity (PD) captures the shared ancestry of species, and is increasingly being recognized as a valuable conservation currency. Regionally, }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_11}\proptype30{\staticval PD frequently covaries closely with species richness; however, variation in speciation and extinction rates and/or the biogeographic history of lineages can result in significant deviation. Locally, these differences may be pronounced. Rapid recent specia}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_12}\proptype30{\staticval tion or high temporal turnover of lineages can result in low PD but high richness. In contrast, rare dispersal events, for example, between biomes, can elevate PD but have only small impact on richness. To date, environmental predictors of species richnes}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_13}\proptype30{\staticval s have been well studied but global models explaining variation in PD are lacking. Here, we contrast the global distribution of PD versus species richness for terrestrial mammals. We show that an environmental model of lineage diversification can predict }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_14}\proptype30{\staticval well the discrepancy in the distribution of these two variables in some places, for example, South America and Africa but not others, such as Southeast Asia. When we have information on multiple diversity indices, conservation efforts directed towards max}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_15}\proptype30{\staticval imizing one currency or another (e. g. species richness versus PD) should also consider the underlying processes that have shaped their distributions.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2011"]]\}, "title": "Phylogenetic diversity as a window into the evolutiona}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_16}\proptype30{\staticval ry and biogeographic histories of present-day richness gradients for mammals", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=7b3e1ef4-26a0-48b8-b387-ffd7036351d7"], "id": "ITEM-2"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_2}\proptype30{\staticval ; Davies and Buckley 2011)", "formattedCitation": "(Purvis et al. 2000; Davies and Buckley 2011)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Science", "ISSN": "00368075", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_3}\proptype30{\staticval ": "", "family": "Purvis", "parse-names": false, "given": "Andy"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Agapow", "parse-names": false, "given": "Paul Michael"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-droppi}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_4}\proptype30{\staticval ng-particle": "", "family": "Gittleman", "parse-names": false, "given": "John L."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Mace", "parse-names": false, "given": "Georgina M."\}], "id": "ITEM-1", "DOI": "10.1126/scie}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_5}\proptype30{\staticval nce.288.5464.328", "abstract": "The hierarchical nature of phylogenies means that random extinction of species affects a smaller fraction of higher taxa, and so the total amount of evolutionary history lost may be comparatively slight. However, current ex}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_6}\proptype30{\staticval tinction risk is not phylogenetically random. We show the potentially severe implications of the clumped nature of threat for the loss of biodiversity. An additional 120 avian and mammalian genera are at risk compared with the number predicted under rando}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_7}\proptype30{\staticval m extinction. We estimate that the prospective extra loss of mammalian evolutionary history alone would be equivalent to losing a monotypic phylum.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2000"]]\}, "title": "Nonrandom extinction and the loss of evolutionary history}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_8}\proptype30{\staticval ", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=170d32b6-54ba-46d4-9b5c-837baf5c2c14"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}, \{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences", "ISSN": "0}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8pi2vtRG0G_9}\proptype30{\staticval 9628436", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Davies", "parse-names": false, "given": "Jonathan T."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Buckley", "parse-n}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Fick and Hijmans 2017)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Fick and Hijmans 2017)", "formattedCitat}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_10}\proptype30{\staticval 88", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Fick", "parse-names": false, "given": "Stephen E."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Hijmans", "parse-names": f}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_11}\proptype30{\staticval alse, "given": "Robert J."\}], "id": "ITEM-1", "issue": "12", "ISBN": "1097-0088", "volume": "37"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=4030d5d7-5a91-4a0b-b8ec-6cbe95ef6a67"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_2}\proptype30{\staticval ion": "(Fick and Hijmans 2017)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"page": "4302-4315", "DOI": "10.1002/joc.5086", "abstract": "We created a new dataset of spatially interpolated monthly climate data for global land areas at a very high spatial resolution }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_3}\proptype30{\staticval (approximately 1\\u2009km2). We included monthly temperature (minimum, maximum and average), precipitation, solar radiation, vapour pressure and wind speed, aggregated across a target temporal range of 1970\\u20132000, using data from between 9000 and 60\\u2}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_4}\proptype30{\staticval 009000 weather stations. Weather station data were interpolated using thin-plate splines with covariates including elevation, distance to the coast and three satellite-derived covariates: maximum and minimum land surface temperature as well as cloud cover}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_5}\proptype30{\staticval , obtained with the MODIS satellite platform. Interpolation was done for 23 regions of varying size depending on station density. Satellite data improved prediction accuracy for temperature variables 5\\u201315% (0.07\\u20130.17\\u00a0\\u00b0C), particularly }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_6}\proptype30{\staticval for areas with a low station density, although prediction error remained high in such regions for all climate variables. Contributions of satellite covariates were mostly negligible for the other variables, although their importance varied by region. In c}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_7}\proptype30{\staticval ontrast to the common approach to use a single model formulation for the entire world, we constructed the final product by selecting the best performing model for each region and variable. Global cross-validation correlations were\\u2009\\u2265\\u20090.99 fo}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_8}\proptype30{\staticval r temperature and humidity, 0.86 for precipitation and 0.76 for wind speed. The fact that most of our climate surface estimates were only marginally improved by use of satellite covariates highlights the importance having a dense, high-quality network of }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_8uuVnWM6XG_9}\proptype30{\staticval climate station data.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2017"]]\}, "title": "WorldClim 2: new 1-km spatial resolution climate surfaces for global land areas", "type": "article-journal", "container-title": "International Journal of Climatology", "ISSN": "109700}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_A12doGx1Nn_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Ratter et al. 1997)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Ratter et al. 1997)", "formattedCitation": }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_A12doGx1Nn_2}\proptype30{\staticval "(Ratter et al. 1997)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Annals of botany", "ISSN": "0305-7364", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Ratter", "parse-names": false, "given": "James }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_A12doGx1Nn_3}\proptype30{\staticval Alexander"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Ribeiro", "parse-names": false, "given": "Jos\\u00e9 Felipe"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Bridgewater", "parse}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_A12doGx1Nn_4}\proptype30{\staticval -names": false, "given": "Samuel"\}], "page": "223-230", "id": "ITEM-1", "publisher": "Elsevier", "issue": "3", "volume": "80", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["1997"]]\}, "title": "The Brazilian cerrado vegetation and threats to its biodiversity", "type": "arti}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_A12doGx1Nn_5}\proptype30{\staticval cle-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=9eb2a68c-8b91-489b-bdc8-ca3abf7d763c"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Zamudio et al. 2016)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Zamudio et al. 2016)", "formattedCitation"}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_10}\proptype30{\staticval ", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Bell", "parse-names": false, "given": "Rayna C."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Mason", "parse-names": false, "given": "Nicholas A."\}], "id": "ITEM}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_11}\proptype30{\staticval -1", "issue": "29", "volume": "113"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=8d6a2dd9-226f-4928-b253-2d7254c14117"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_2}\proptype30{\staticval : "(Zamudio et al. 2016)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"page": "8041-8048", "DOI": "10.1073/pnas.1602237113", "abstract": "Almost 30 y ago, the field of intraspecific phylogeography laid the foundation for spatially explicit and genealogically inform}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_3}\proptype30{\staticval ed studies of population divergence. With new methods and markers, the focus in phylogeography shifted to previously unrecognized geographic genetic variation, thus reducing the attention paid to phenotypic variation in those same diverging lineages. Alth}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_4}\proptype30{\staticval ough phenotypic differences among lineages once provided the main data for studies of evolutionary change, the mechanisms shaping phenotypic differentiation and their integration with intraspecific genetic structure have been underexplored in phylogeograp}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_5}\proptype30{\staticval hic studies. However, phenotypes are targets of selection and play important roles in species performance, recognition, and diversification. Here, we focus on three questions. First, how can phenotypes elucidate mechanisms underlying concordant or idiosyn}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_6}\proptype30{\staticval cratic responses of vertebrate species evolving in shared landscapes? Second, what mechanisms underlie the concordance or discordance of phenotypic and phylogeographic differentiation? Third, how can phylogeography contribute to our understanding of funct}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_7}\proptype30{\staticval ional phenotypic evolution? We demonstrate that the integration of phenotypic data extends the reach of phylogeography to explain the origin and maintenance of biodiversity. Finally, we stress the importance of natural history collections as sources of hi}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_8}\proptype30{\staticval gh-quality phenotypic data that span temporal and spatial axes.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2016"]]\}, "title": "Phenotypes in phylogeography: Species\\u2019 traits, environmental variation, and vertebrate diversification", "type": "article-journal", "con}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_BaKI4GfTBr_9}\proptype30{\staticval tainer-title": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences", "ISSN": "0027-8424", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Zamudio", "parse-names": false, "given": "Kelly R."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Mayle 2004; Carnaval et al. 2009; Werneck 2011; Collevatti et al. 2012; Werneck et al. 2012; Ledo }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_10}\proptype30{\staticval predicts genetic diversity in the Brazilian Atlantic forest hotspot.", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=2397c2e0-c923-4d31-a4b3-f66836416653"], "id": "ITEM-2"\}, \{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Quaternary Scie}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_11}\proptype30{\staticval nce Reviews", "ISSN": "02773791", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Werneck", "parse-names": false, "given": "Fernanda P."\}], "page": "13-14", "id": "ITEM-3", "DOI": "10.1016/j.quascirev.2011.03.009}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_12}\proptype30{\staticval ", "abstract": "The eastern-central South American open vegetation biomes occur across an extensive range of environmental conditions and are organized diagonally including three complexly interacting tropical/sub-tropical biomes. Seasonally Dry Tropical }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_13}\proptype30{\staticval Forests (SDTFs), Cerrado, and Chaco biomes are seasonally stressed by drought, characterized by significant plant and animal endemism, high levels of diversity, and highly endangered. However, these open biomes have been overlooked in biogeographic studie}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_14}\proptype30{\staticval s and conservation projects in South America, especially regarding fauna studies. Here I compile and evaluate the biogeographic hypotheses previously proposed for the diversification of these three major open biomes, specifically their distributions locat}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_15}\proptype30{\staticval ed eastern and southern of Andes. My goal is to generate predictions and provide a background for testable hypotheses. I begin by investigating both continental (inter-biome) and regional (within-biome) levels, and I then provide a biogeographical summary}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_16}\proptype30{\staticval  for these regions. I also suggest how novel molecular-based historical biogeographic/phylogeographic approaches could contribute to the resolution of long-standing questions, identify potential target fauna groups for development of these lines of study,}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_17}\proptype30{\staticval  and describe fertile future research agendas. \\u00a9 2011 Elsevier Ltd.", "volume": "30", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2011"]]\}, "title": "The diversification of eastern South American open vegetation biomes: Historical biogeography and perspectives", "ty}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_18}\proptype30{\staticval pe": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=34c9a956-62f0-4707-9c33-d2fdd784a518"], "id": "ITEM-3"\}, \{"itemData": \{"type": "article-journal", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "f}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_19}\proptype30{\staticval amily": "Collevatti", "parse-names": false, "given": "RG"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Lima-Ribeiro", "parse-names": false, "given": "MS"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_2}\proptype30{\staticval and Colli 2017; Costa et al. 2018)", "manualFormatting": "(Mayle 2004; Carnaval et al. 2009; Werneck 2011; Collevatti et al. 2012; Werneck et al. 2012; Ledo and Colli 2017; Costa et al. 2018, ", "previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Mayle 2004; Carnaval et al.}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_20}\proptype30{\staticval ": "", "family": "Souza-Neto", "parse-names": false, "given": "AC"\}], "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2012"]]\}, "title": "Recovering the demographical history of a Brazilian Cerrado tree species Caryocar brasiliense: coupling ecological niche modeling and coa}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_21}\proptype30{\staticval lescent analyses", "id": "ITEM-4"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=87de6a29-52a5-3ac2-ade9-140fa1c60fb1"], "id": "ITEM-4"\}, \{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Journal of Biogeography", "ISSN": "03050270", "author": [\{"dropping-particle":}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_22}\proptype30{\staticval  "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Werneck", "parse-names": false, "given": "Fernanda P."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Nogueira", "parse-names": false, "given": "Cristiano"\}, \{"d}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_23}\proptype30{\staticval ropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Colli", "parse-names": false, "given": "Guarino R."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Sites", "parse-names": false, "given": "Jack}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_24}\proptype30{\staticval  W."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Costa", "parse-names": false, "given": "Gabriel C."\}], "id": "ITEM-5", "DOI": "10.1111/j.1365-2699.2012.02715.x", "abstract": "Aim To investigate the historical distrib}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_25}\proptype30{\staticval ution of the Cerrado across Quaternary climatic fluctuations and to generate historical stability maps to test: (1) whether the historical climate stability hypothesis explains squamate reptile richness in the Cerrado; and (2) the hypothesis of Pleistocen}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_26}\proptype30{\staticval e connections between savannas located north and south of Amazonia. Location The Cerrado, a savanna biome and a global biodiversity hotspot distributed mainly in central Brazil. Methods We generated occurrence datasets from 1000 presence points randomly s}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_27}\proptype30{\staticval elected from the entire distribution of the Cerrado, as determined by two spatial definitions. We modelled the potential Cerrado distribution by implementing a maximum-entropy machine-learning algorithm across four time projections: current, mid-Holocene }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_28}\proptype30{\staticval (6 ka), Last Glacial Maximum (LGM, 21 ka) and Last Interglacial (LIG, 120 ka). We generated historical stability maps (refugial areas) by overlapping presence/absence projections of all scenarios, and checked consistencies with qualitative comparisons wit}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_29}\proptype30{\staticval h available fossil pollen records. We built a spatially explicit simultaneous autoregressive model to explore the relationship between current climate, climatic stability, and squamate species richness. Results Models predicted the LGM and LIG as the peri}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_3}\proptype30{\staticval  2009; Werneck 2011; Collevatti et al. 2012; Werneck et al. 2012; Ledo and Colli 2017; Costa et al. 2018)", "formattedCitation": "(Mayle 2004; Carnaval et al. 2009; Werneck 2011; Collevatti et al. 2012; Werneck et al. 2012; Ledo and Colli 2017; Costa et a}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_30}\proptype30{\staticval ods of narrowest and widest Cerrado distributions, respectively, and were largely corroborated by palynological evidence. We found evidence for two savanna corridors (eastern coastal during the LIG, and Andean during the LGM) and predicted a large refugia}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_31}\proptype30{\staticval l area in the north-eastern Cerrado (Serra Geral de Goias refugium). Variables related to climatic stability predicted squamate richness better than present climatic variables did. Main conclusions Our results indicate that Bolivian savannas should be inc}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_32}\proptype30{\staticval luded within the Cerrado range and that the Cerrados biogeographical counterparts are not Chaco and Caatinga but rather the disjunct savannas of the Guyana shield plateaus. Climatic stability is a good predictor of Cerrado squamate richness, and our stabi}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_33}\proptype30{\staticval lity maps could be used in future studies to test diversity patterns and genetic signatures of different taxonomic groups and as a higher-order landscape biodiversity surrogate for conservation planning.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2012"]]\}, "title": "C}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_34}\proptype30{\staticval limatic stability in the Brazilian Cerrado: Implications for biogeographical connections of South American savannas, species richness and conservation in a biodiversity hotspot", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uui}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_35}\proptype30{\staticval d=da8041d0-dbd4-451a-b74a-38277906efdd"], "id": "ITEM-5"\}, \{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Journal of Biogeography", "ISSN": "13652699", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Ledo", "parse-names": fal}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_36}\proptype30{\staticval se, "given": "Roger Maia Dias"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Colli", "parse-names": false, "given": "Guarino Rinaldi"\}], "id": "ITEM-6", "DOI": "10.1111/jbi.13049", "abstract": "Aim To assess ancient bio}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_37}\proptype30{\staticval tic connections between the Amazon Forest (AmF) and the Atlantic Forest (AtF) based on environmental niche modelling (ENM), palaeobiological, and molecular evidence; to test Por (1992)'s hypothesis of the south-eastern\\u2014north-western (SE\\u2014NW) rout}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_38}\proptype30{\staticval e as the most important route in terms of frequency and duration; to evaluate past climatic conditions associated with the routes. Location South America. Methods We generated random points in climate space of AmF and AtF and identified two major climatic}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_39}\proptype30{\staticval  groups in the shared environmental space (colder and warmer) with a K-means cluster analysis. We modelled each climatic group using eleven algorithms of ENM and selected the best model, projecting the results back to 120 ka. We used published data on Sou}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_4}\proptype30{\staticval l. 2018)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"container-title": "Journal of Quaternary Science", "ISSN": "0267-8179", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Mayle", "parse-names": false, "given": "Francis}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_40}\proptype30{\staticval th American palaeopalynology, speleothem and travertine chronology for model validation. We also accessed vertebrate molecular studies and extracted the split timing of lineages distributed both in the AmF and the AtF to test Por (1992)'s hypothesis in mo}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_41}\proptype30{\staticval re ancient times. Results Palynological and speleothem studies supported the results of our ENM models, indicating expansion of cold-adapted species along the SE\\u2014NW and NE routes in the LGM. The SE\\u2014NW route was also supported in the LIG, however}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_42}\proptype30{\staticval , involving warm-adapted species. Our results support Por (1992)'s hypothesis and suggest that the SE\\u2014NW was established more than once in the past, involving different plant communities each time, adapted to different temperature conditions. Vertebr}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_43}\proptype30{\staticval ate molecular studies also support Por (1992)'s hypothesis and suggest that the SE\\u2014NW route was established since the Andean uplift. Main Conclusions The SE\\u2014NW route is the most ancient connection route between the AmF and the AtF and probably w}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_44}\proptype30{\staticval as established since the Andean uplift and the formation of the South American monsoon system. This route was established many times in the past, alternating by the distribution expansion of cold-adapted and warm-adapted plant communities.", "issued": \{"d}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_45}\proptype30{\staticval ate-parts": [["2017"]]\}, "title": "The historical connections between the Amazon and the Atlantic Forest revisited", "type": "article-journal"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=624f525d-19bc-4437-9c41-b184dbeb45ae"], "id": "ITEM-6"\}, \{"i}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_46}\proptype30{\staticval temData": \{"page": "285-297", "DOI": "10.1111/geb.12694", "abstract": "Aim: The aim was to examine the links between past biome stability, vegetation dynamics and biodiversity patterns. Location: South America. Time period: Last 30,000 years. Major taxa s}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_47}\proptype30{\staticval tudied: Plants. Methods: We classified South America into major biomes according to their dominant plant functional groups (grasses, trees and shrubs) and ran a random forest (RF) classification with data on current climate. We then fitted the algorithm t}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_48}\proptype30{\staticval o predict biome distributions for every 1,000 years back to 21,000 yr BP and estimated biome stability by counting how many times a change in climate was predicted to shift a grid cell from one biome to another. We compared our model-based stability map w}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_49}\proptype30{\staticval ith empirical estimates from selected pollen records covering the past 30 kyr in terms of vegetation shifts, changes in species composition and time-lag of vegetation responses. Results: We found a strong correlation between our habitat stability map and }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_5}\proptype30{\staticval  E"\}], "page": "713-720", "id": "ITEM-1", "publisher": "Wiley Online Library", "issue": "7", "volume": "19", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2004"]]\}, "title": "Assessment of the Neotropical dry forest refugia hypothesis in the light of palaeoecological data }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_50}\proptype30{\staticval regional vegetation dynamics. Four scenarios emerged according to the way forest distribution shifted during a climate change. Each scenario related to specific regional features of biome stability and diversity, allowing us to formulate specific predicti}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_51}\proptype30{\staticval ons on how taxonomic, genetic and functional components of biodiversity might be impacted by modern climate change. Main conclusions: Our validated map of biome stability provides important baseline information for studying the impacts of past climate on }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_52}\proptype30{\staticval biodiversity in South America. By focusing exclusively on climatic changes of manifested relevance (i.e., those resulting in significant habitat changes), it provides a novel perspective that complements previous datasets and allows scientists to explore }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_53}\proptype30{\staticval new questions and hypotheses at the local, regional and continental scales.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2018"]]\}, "title": "Biome stability in South America over the last 30 kyr: inferences from long-term vegetation dynamics and habitat modelling", "typ}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_54}\proptype30{\staticval e": "article-journal", "container-title": "Global Ecology and Biogeography", "ISSN": "14668238", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Costa", "parse-names": false, "given": "Gabriel C."\}, \{"dropping-pa}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_55}\proptype30{\staticval rticle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Hampe", "parse-names": false, "given": "Arndt"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Ledru", "parse-names": false, "given": "Marie Pierre"\}, \{"d}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_DhU5V3azBm_56}\proptype30{\staticval ropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Martinez", "parse-names": false, "given": "Pablo A."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "su