uction to Statistical Learning", "publisher-place": "New York", "PMID": "10911016", "ISBN": "978-1-4614-7137-0"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=c0600082-d7ef-457a-843b-aa0a7}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_GWiFGcu3YM_7}\proptype30{\staticval 9ed76a8"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Paranjpe et al. 2013)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Paranjpe et al. 2013)", "formattedCitatio}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_10}\proptype30{\staticval en": "Elizabeth"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Patten", "parse-names": false, "given": "Amy"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Cooper", "parse-names": fals}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_11}\proptype30{\staticval e, "given": "Robert D."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Sinervo", "parse-names": false, "given": "Barry"\}], "id": "ITEM-1", "issue": "7", "volume": "3"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=6}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_12}\proptype30{\staticval 53e27d4-7cb0-4b72-ab0f-c50fe9a7abf4"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_2}\proptype30{\staticval n": "(Paranjpe et al. 2013)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"page": "1977-1991", "DOI": "10.1002/ece3.614", "abstract": "Natural populations respond to selection pressures like increasing local temperatures in many ways, including plasticity and adapta}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_IIAgCcEI0V_3}\proptype30{\staticval tion. To predict the response of ectotherms like lizards to local temperature increase, it is essential to estimate phenotypic variation in and determin