ame Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_3}\proptype30{\staticval iction of animal behavior. The Mojave Desert biome and the desert iguana are used to illustrate these principles. A transient energy balance model for animals in an outdoor environment is presented. The concepts and relationships have been tested in a win}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_4}\proptype30{\staticval d tunnel, in a simulated desert, and in the field. The animal model requires anatomical information and knowledge of the thermoregulatory responses of the animal. The micrometeorological model requires only basic meteorological parameters and two soil phy}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_5}\proptype30{\staticval sical properties as inputs. Tests of the model in the field show agreement between predicted and measured temperatures above and below the surface of about 2 to 3\\u00b0C. The animal and micrometeorological models are combined to predict daily and seasonal}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_6}\proptype30{\staticval  activity patterns, available times for predator-prey interaction, and daily, seasonal and annual requirements for food and water. It is shown that food, water and the thermal environment can limit animal activity, and furthermore, the controlling limit c}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_7}\proptype30{\staticval hanges with season. Actual observations of activity patterns and our predictions show close agreement, in many cases, and pose intriguing questions in those situations where agreement does not exist. This type of modeling can be used to further study pred}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_8}\proptype30{\staticval ator-prey interactions, to study how changes in the environment might affect animal behavior, and to answer other important ecological and physiological questions.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["1973"]]\}, "title": "Behavioral implications of mechanistic ec}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zP9v0ta0aF_9}\proptype30{\staticval ology", "type": "article-journal", "container-title": "Oecologia", "ISSN": "0029-8519", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Porter", "parse-names": false, "given": "Warren P"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_1}\proptype30{\staticval ADDIN CSL_CITATION \{"schema": "https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json", "mendeley": \{"previouslyFormattedCitation": "(Huey 1991; Walther et al. 2002; Kearney and Porter 2009)", "plainTextFormattedCitation": "(Huey 1}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_10}\proptype30{\staticval arse-names": false, "given": "Raymond B."\}], "PMID": "28", "ISBN": "00030147", "volume": "137"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=5c085a2a-d41b-4515-872b-c4bb47914882"], "id": "ITEM-1"\}, \{"itemData": \{"page": "389-395", "DOI": "10.1038/41}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_11}\proptype30{\staticval 6389a", "abstract": "There is now ample evidence of the ecological impacts of recent climate change, from polar terrestrial to tropical marine environments. The responses of both flora and fauna span an array of ecosystems and organizational hierarchies, }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_12}\proptype30{\staticval from the species to the community levels. Despite continued uncertainty as to community and ecosystem trajectories under global change, our review exposes a coherent pattern of ecological change across systems. Although we are only at an early stage in th}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_13}\proptype30{\staticval e projected trends of global warming, ecological responses to recent climate change are already clearly visible.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2002"]]\}, "id": "ITEM-2", "type": "article-journal", "container-title": "Nature", "ISSN": "0028-0836", "author":}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_14}\proptype30{\staticval  [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Walther", "parse-names": false, "given": "Gian-Reto"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Post", "parse-names": false, "given": }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_15}\proptype30{\staticval "Eric"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Convey", "parse-names": false, "given": "Peter"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Menzel", "parse-names": false, "give}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_16}\proptype30{\staticval n": "Annette"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Parmesan", "parse-names": false, "given": "Camille"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Beebee", "parse-names": f}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_17}\proptype30{\staticval alse, "given": "Trevor J. C."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Fromentin", "parse-names": false, "given": "Jean-Marc"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Hoegh-}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_18}\proptype30{\staticval Guldberg", "parse-names": false, "given": "Ove"\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Bairlein", "parse-names": false, "given": "Franz"\}], "title": "Ecological responses to recent climate change", "PMID": "11919}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_19}\proptype30{\staticval 621", "issue": "6879", "ISBN": "0028-0836", "volume": "416"\}, "uris": ["http://www.mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=f17b5e8d-4790-40c4-9e64-3189c9702495"], "id": "ITEM-2"\}, \{"itemData": \{"page": "334-350", "DOI": "10.1111/j.1461-0248.2008.01277.x", "abstract"}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_2}\proptype30{\staticval 991; Walther et al. 2002; Kearney and Porter 2009)", "formattedCitation": "(Huey 1991; Walther et al. 2002; Kearney and Porter 2009)"\}, "citationItems": [\{"itemData": \{"page": "S91-S115", "DOI": "10.1086/285141", "abstract": "By determining the microclima}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_20}\proptype30{\staticval : "Species distribution models (SDMs) use spatial environmental data to make inferences on species\\u2019 range limits and habitat suitability. Conceptually, these models aim to determine and map components of a species\\u2019 ecological niche through space}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_21}\proptype30{\staticval  and time, and they have become important tools in pure and applied ecology and evolutionary biology. Most approaches are correlative in that they statistically link spatial data to species distribution records. An alternative strategy is to explicitly in}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_22}\proptype30{\staticval corporate the mechanistic links between the functional traits of organisms and their environments into SDMs. Here, we review how the principles of biophysical ecology can be used to link spatial data to the physiological responses and constraints of organ}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_23}\proptype30{\staticval isms. This provides a mechanistic view of the fundamental niche which can then be mapped to the landscape to infer range constraints. We show how physiologically based SDMs can be developed for different organisms in different environmental contexts. Mech}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_24}\proptype30{\staticval anistic SDMs have different strengths and weaknesses to correlative approaches, and there are many exciting and unexplored prospects for integrating the two approaches. As physiological knowledge becomes better integrated into SDMs, we will make more robu}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_25}\proptype30{\staticval st predictions of range shifts in novel or non-equilibrium contexts such as invasions, translocations, climate change and evolutionary shifts.", "issued": \{"date-parts": [["2009"]]\}, "id": "ITEM-3", "type": "article-journal", "container-title": "Ecology L}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_26}\proptype30{\staticval etters", "ISSN": "1461023X", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Kearney", "parse-names": false, "given": "Michael R."\}, \{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": }{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_27}\proptype30{\staticval "Porter", "parse-names": false, "given": "Warren"\}], "title": "Mechanistic niche modelling: Combining physiological and spatial data to predict species' ranges", "PMID": "19292794", "issue": "4", "ISBN": "1461-0248", "volume": "12"\}, "uris": ["http://www.}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_28}\proptype30{\staticval mendeley.com/documents/?uuid=d9d8801d-7413-4ef1-a268-b72b19eb04bb"], "id": "ITEM-3"\}], "properties": \{"noteIndex": 0\}\}}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_3}\proptype30{\staticval tes that an animal experiences, habitats influence an animal's physiological capacities and ultimately its demographic and ecological performance. As a result, the ecology of organisms-especially of ectotherms-can be profoundly affected by the physiologic}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_4}\proptype30{\staticval al consequences of habitat selection. Early ecologists such as Shelford and Chapman appreciated these issues, but most later ones tended to ignore physiology and instead focused on biotic interactions (e.g., competition). Recent technical and conceptual d}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_5}\proptype30{\staticval evelopments are now fostering a reintroduction of physiology into ecology. For issues relevant to thermal physiology, three steps are involved. First, the microclimates available in a habitat must be mapped. For ectotherms, this involves determining the o}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_6}\proptype30{\staticval perative environmental temperatures (Te)-that is, the potential body temperatures available in a habitat. Biophysical techniques can now generate Te maps with considerable accuracy. Second, the physiological effects of body temperature must be quantified.}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_7}\proptype30{\staticval  This requires laboratory studies of the effect of temperature on key performance traits. Third, the physiological suitability of habitats can be predicted by integrating the above environmental and physiological data. Analyses of the physiological conseq}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_8}\proptype30{\staticval uences of habitat selection are exemplified in several case studies, and the importance of considering food and other factors in the analyses is stressed. An extension to endotherms is briefly discussed.", "type": "article-journal", "issued": \{"date-parts}{\propname Mendeley_Bookmark_zhJETsJODn_9}\proptype30{\staticval ": [["1991"]]\}, "title": "Physiological consequences of habitat selection", "id": "ITEM-1", "container-title": "American Naturalist", "ISSN": "0003-0147", "author": [\{"dropping-particle": "", "suffix": "", "non-dropping-particle": "", "family": "Huey", "p}{\propname ScaleCrop}\proptype11{\staticval 0}{\propname ShareDoc}\proptype11{\staticval 0}}\deftab720\deftab720\deftab720
